docs.abstract: And why, even though I hate it, small talk is so important.
docs.snippet: And why, even though I hate it, small talk is so important.
docs.lead_paragraph: A friend recently wondered aloud whether she has a sign around her neck, invisible to her, that solicits strangers for advice. She enjoyed a respite from unsolicited feedback when we were at our most vigilant about social distancing during the Covid-19 pandemic, but with a shift back toward normalcy, the fragile détente seems to have been called off. During a recent routine trip to her favorite cafe, no fewer than four people offered her advice on crossing the street, choosing a pastry and reading material. She takes it in stride but she knew I would be a sympathetic ear: I am on record as being very cautious about giving advice.

headline.main: Why Everyone Is Always Giving Unsolicited Advice

docs.abstract: On the virtues of ignoring famous people’s irrelevant opinions.
docs.snippet: On the virtues of ignoring famous people’s irrelevant opinions.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last week, Kyrie Irving, the star guard for the Brooklyn Nets, missed the team’s media day at the Barclays Center. There was much speculation that Irving actually could not legally enter the building because of New York City’s proof-of-vaccination requirements, which, in turn, could preclude him from playing any games in cities with similar mandates. Irving, instead, chose to talk to reporters by video conference. When asked if he planned to play home games this season, Irving said, “Please respect my privacy regarding home games, what’s happening with my vaccination.”

headline.main: Should You Care About Unvaccinated N.B.A. Players?
headline.print_headline: Should You Care What Athletes Think?

docs.abstract: Some executives who operate nonprofit homeless shelters have paid themselves generously, even as homelessness has surged to record levels in New York City.
docs.snippet: Some executives who operate nonprofit homeless shelters have paid themselves generously, even as homelessness has surged to record levels in New York City.
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s Monday. We’ll look at how executives at nonprofits that run homeless shelters earned large salaries, employed family members and sometimes doubled as for-profit vendors who provided services to their charities. And we’ll look at a school in Queens that counts Japan’s new prime minister as an alumnus.

headline.main: The Homeless Shelter Executive Who Earns $1 Million a Year
